<TD VALIGN=TOP><!--NOLStoryBody-->


	<SPAN CLASS="date">Monday, 19 June, 2000, 12:41 GMT 13:41 UK
</SPAN>
	<DIV CLASS="headlinestory"><B>Farmer jury to be questioned</B><BR></DIV>
	<FONT FACE="sans-serif" SIZE="2">
	
	
		
		<DIV CLASS="inlineimage">
		<IMG alt="Tony Martin" vspace="0" border=0 width="300" height="180" src="/web/20000711062804im_/http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/725000/images/_727261_martin300.jpg"><BR CLEAR="all">
		
			<DIV CLASS="caption"><SMALL>Tony Martin: Taking one day at a time</SMALL><BR></DIV>
		
		</DIV>
		
	
	



	
	
		
	





	<DIV CLASS="bodytext">Jurors in the case of Tony Martin - the Norfolk farmer jailed for murdering an intruder at his isolated farmhouse - are to be questioned over whether they were intimidated.
<P>
Three Court of Appeal judges ruled that police could take the unusual step of submitting written questions to the six men and six women.
<P>
Lord Justice Rose, Mr Justice Harrison and Mr Justice Tomlinson said the questions could be put "as soon as possible".
<P>
The decision came as Martin began an appeal to overturn his conviction.
<P>
The 55-year-old was found guilty of murdering Fred Barras, 16, and wounding his accomplice Brendan Fearon, 30, with a shotgun.
<P>
Martin, of Bleak House, Emneth Hungate, near Emneth, Norfolk, was sentenced to life imprisonment at Norwich Crown Court in April.
<br>
	
		
			<BR CLEAR="all"></FONT><TABLE CELLSPACING="2" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="154" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2"><TR><TD><FONT FACE="sans-serif" SIZE="2">
		
		<DIV CLASS="inlineimage">
		<IMG alt="Fred Barras" vspace="0" border=0 width="150" height="180" src="/web/20000711062804im_/http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/725000/images/_727261_barras150.jpg"><BR CLEAR="all">
		
			<DIV CLASS="caption"><SMALL>Fred Barras: Died from gun wounds</SMALL><BR></DIV>
		
		</DIV>
		</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<FONT FACE="sans-serif" SIZE="2">

	
	



	
	
		
	


<P>
His solicitor, Nick Makin, said he was delighted there would be swift action over the allegations of intimidation.
<P>
Martin's lawyers say the main plank of their appeal is that the judge misdirected the jury and their client did not receive a fair trial.
<P>
So far, little hard evidence of jury intimidation has been made public. 
<P>
No juror has complained to the police and after an investigation, court officials decided to take no further action.
<P>
But there were reports shortly after the verdict that some of the jury members felt threatened in the courtroom.
<P>
<B>Self-defence</B>
<P>
The farmer, who claimed he had fired in self-defence, has since described the death of Barras as "regrettable" and says he had not intended to kill him.
<P>
The case provoked widespread debate over issues of self-defence and rural policing.
<P>
A date has not yet been set for the full appeal hearing. 
<P>
</DIV>
	</FONT>






